-Phosgene and chlorine gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;

-Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;

-Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;

-Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistent safe work-practices;

-Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - including equipment testing and inspection;

-A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible 
hazards (this is called Management of Change);

-Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;

-Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,

-Safety permitting procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding and other 
maintenance activities.

0.5 FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

The Burkville, AL site has an outstanding record of accident prevention that demonstrates its commitment to 
public and worker safety. Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how 
to prevent future occurrences.

EPA requires that all incidents involving regulated chemicals that resulted in any off-site impact or significant 
on-site impacts be reported in this document. During the previous five-year period (June 21, 1999 through 
the date of this report), one such incident occurred at the plant. On January 31, 2001, GE employees were 
in the process of draining a vessel when the hose they were using failed. This allowed the contents of the 
vessel to drain outside the enclosure in which the vessel was housed. The resulting release accounted for a 
loss of a large amount of acidic water with a small amount (2.5 Pounds) of phosgene dissolved into it. As a 
